We have 14 variables across 1309 observations (seen from the environment display); pclass, survived, name, sex, age, sibsp, parch, ticket, fare, cabin, embarked, boat, body, home.dest Notice the way the summaries differ for strings vs.numerical data. Keep in mind that some numerical data is categorical. survived, for instance, is binary and it would not make sense to find quantiles and averages for that variable. We see we have integer, numerical, and factor variables. Factors are the string-type variables.

Note that boat is considered a factor as it refers to boat number, so taking an average of boat numbers would not make sense (would you take an average of zip-codes?).

In statistical practice, columns are always associated with the different variables while rows are associated with the different observations.

Subsetting Data

Lets create a new dataframe tdat_sub that we will treat as a subdataframe for us to play with.

tdat_sub <- tdat

We now want to produce a dataframe based on a subset of the columns. Recall our variable names.

names(tdat)
 [1] "pclass"    "survived"  "name"      "sex"       "age"       "sibsp"     "parch"    
 [8] "ticket"    "fare"      "cabin"     "embarked"  "boat"      "body"      "home.dest"

Let us keep pclass, survived, sex, age, and fare.

keep <- c("pclass", "survived", "sex", "age", "fare") #gives us a vector of strings defining the variables (columns) we wish to keep.
tdat_sub <- tdat_sub[keep] #overwrite tdat_sub--be careful with overwriting! If you're not sure whether you wish to overwrite, better to create a new variable to manipulate!
summary(tdat_sub)

first_passenger["fare"] #We can also extract the value for the particular variable as follows.

Lets combine row and column subsetting. The following will give us a 10x3 data frame of the first 10 rows with the variables: pclass, survived, and name.

keep2 <- c("pclass", "survived", "name")
subset <- tdat[1:10,keep2]
subset

The binary variable survived takes on value 1 if the person survived, and 0 if they did not. We can subset based on logical tests. We will take our 10x3 data frame and reduce it to a subdataframe containing just the survivors.

subset_surv <- subset[subset$survived == 1,] #keep rows where the value of "survived" is 1 while retaining all columns.
subset_surv

We can now subset the larger data file tdat by survivors.

tdat_surv <- tdat[tdat$survived == 1,]

If we examine tdat_survLEQ30, we find that there are no observations containing N/A for the age variable. Those were dropped by the logical (make sure you understand the caveats of dropping observations from a model; you also have the option of replacing empty values with an estimator determined from the nonempty data). In an ideal dataset, there are no missing values, but this rarely happens in the real world.

Data Visualisation

Lets now produce some plots of our data.. Lets produce a histogram for the variable age.

qplot(age, data=tdat, geom="histogram", binwidth=10)

qplot(age, data=tdat, geom="histogram", binwidth=5)

qplot(age, data=tdat, geom="histogram", binwidth=3)

qplot(age, data=tdat, geom="histogram", binwidth=1)

Remember, a histogram creates classes based on bins (consecutive intervals of the variable).

We can also create a scatterplot of two variables against each other which helps us examine trends. Note that we can add additional commands to capture binary differences in the data.

ggplot() + geom_point(data=tdat, mapping=aes(x=age, y=fare, shape=sex, color=as.factor(survived))) #we use as.factor(survived) to prevent R from treating it as a continuous variable on [0,1].

We can also produce box-and-whisker plots for examine 5-number-summaries (min, \(Q_1\), median, \(Q_3\), max)

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(data=tdat, aes(x=as.factor(survived), y=age), outlier.colour="red")

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(data=tdat, aes(x=as.factor(survived), y=fare), outlier.colour="red")

R uses a simple interquartile range (IQR) outlier classification rule for boxplots.

Linear Models

We will use a different dataset for building a linear model of the form \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \dots + \beta_p X_p\) where \(Y\) is a dependent variable on the independent variables \(X_1, \dots , X_p\). We will use the following accompanying package for Julian Faraways Linear Models with R text.

data(divusa, package="faraway")
summary(divusa)

One might reasonably think there is a strong correlation between marriage and birth. We see from the scatterplot that there seems to be a loose positive correlation. To fit the model \(Y_{birth} = \beta_0 + \beta_{marriage} X_{marriage}\), we use the lm() function.

lmod <- lm(birth ~ marriage, data=divusa)
summary(lmod)

abline(lmod)

We can extend linear models to \(X_1, \dots , X_p\) as mentioned before. An example might be to try to explain divorce as a linear function of the other variables except for year.

lmod2 <- lm(divorce ~ unemployed + femlab + marriage + birth + military, data=divusa)
summary(lmod2)

General Linear Models & Classification (In Progress)

What was the survival rate of the passengers?

mean(tdat$survived)
[1] 0.381971

It was approximately 38.2%.

Can we imagine what sorts of variables may give us a clear seperating boundary for survivability? Lets try the variable sex.

males <- subset(tdat, sex == "male")
females <- subset(tdat, sex == "female")
mean(males$survived)
[1] 0.1909846
mean(females$survived)
[1] 0.7274678

We see an approximate 19.1% survival rate for males and 72.7% survival rate for females. A simple classification rule would be: If \(sex = male \rightarrow survived = 0\) If \(sex = female \rightarrow survived = 1\). What would our classification accuracy be under this rule? Let \(n\) be the total number of observations, \(M\) be the number of non-surviving males, and \(F\) be the number of surviving females. \(\frac{M+F}{n}\) is our expected classification accuracy given the data.

(nrow(males[males$survived == 0,]) + nrow(females[females$survived == 1,])) / nrow(tdat)
[1] 0.7799847

So our expected classification accuracy is approximately 80% given this rule.

What if we wish to incorporate more than just one variable in our classification? We can use a form of regression to produce a classification rule. In order to do this, we will need to split our data into training and validation sets (for validating the classification rule).

We will use a training set size of 80% of the data (rounded down).

train_size <- floor(0.8*nrow(tdat))
train_size #Our training set size.
[1] 1047
set.seed(12345) #Setting a base for the RNG.
train_idx <- sample(seq_len(nrow(tdat)), size=train_size)
train <- tdat[train_idx,]
valid <- tdat[-train_idx,]

We now have our training and validation sets. Let us create a probit regression model. This is a form of general linear model (GLM). We will have to specify a link function as probit within the glm() function. We will use the following predictors: sex, age, sibsp, parch, and fare as predictors for the binary response survived.

probit_model <- glm(survived ~ sex + age + sibsp + parch + fare, family=binomial(link="probit"), data=train) #Don't forget to use the training data, or else we might accidentaly validate the model based on data we used to train it!
summary(probit_model)

As classification rule from the probit regression is: If our predicted response is \(>\) 0.5, classify as a survivor. If otherwise, classify as a nonsurvivor. Not that the predicted responses are in \((0,1)\).

Note that some predicted responses have the NA value. This is due to NA in the predictors. For fixing the NA values in the predictors we can consider averages, interpolation, or regression approaches (with the missing predcitor as the new response). These considerations are discussed in an applied statistics course.
